public class Wheel
extends java.lang.Object
implements IVehiclePart, IDistanceModifierPart

Represents a wheel. This contains data and is the most complicated of the parts as it must keep a more complex type validator than other parts.

Constructor Detail

Wheel

public Wheel(java.lang.String name,
             double timeModifierPercentage,
             double speedModifierPercentage,
             java.util.List<VehicleType>... orderedValidPositions)
Constructor, and the only way to set the characteristics of a Wheel.

Parameters:
name - A name for the type of wheel.
timeModifierPercentage - Amount, expressed as a 100-based percentage, that this wheel affects the time a rider can ride the vehicle. Values lower than -100 will create an invalid wheel.
speedModifierPercentage - Amount, expressed as a 100-based percentage, that this wheel affects the speed of a vehicle. Values lower than -100 will create an invalid wheel.
orderedValidPositions - A set of lists of vehicle types, where each list corresponds to a position. For instance, if two lists are passed, the first will be the vehicles for which this wheel is valid as a FRONT wheel, and the second list will be the vehicles for which this wheel is valid as a REAR wheel. The index is converted to a position based on PartPosition.fromInt(index).

equals

public boolean equals(java.lang.Object other)
Two wheels are equal if: 1. They have the same name. 2. They have the same modifier properties (compared by doubleEquals) 3. They are valid for the same types of vehicles in all possible positions. Note that the validation maps don't necessarily have to be the same, and excess validation positions are ignored. These things are similarly ignored in hashCode.
